<div class="markdown"><div class="admonition is-question"><header class="admonition-header">Question:</header><div class="admonition-body"><p>In regards to Bayes Theorem, what happens when the prior is biased/inaccurate? Is there a way to test how "good" a prior is?</p></div></div></div>


<div class="markdown"><ul><li><p>Often there are multiple reasonable choices for the prior.  </p></li><li><p>We should expect that the prior will differ from the posterior (otherwise there wasn't any point in collecting the data).</p></li><li><p>One common approach is to perform a <strong>sensitivity analysis</strong>, where we repeat the analysis using multiple different priors to see how much the posterior distribution changes. </p></li></ul></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function plot_prior_and_posterior(obs, num_obs, prior; max_y=0)
    @assert 1 &lt;= num_obs 
    @assert 0 &lt;= obs &lt;= num_obs
    x = range(0,stop=1,length=200)
    # Can compute posterior analytically 
    posterior = Beta(prior.α+obs, prior.β+num_obs-obs)
    
    plt = plot(x,pdf.(prior,x), label="Prior", xlabel="p", ylabel="PDF", lweight=2)
    posterior = Beta(prior.α+obs, prior.β+num_obs-obs)
    
    plot!(plt,x,pdf.(posterior,x), label="Posterior", lweight=2)
    frac_success = obs/num_obs
    if max_y==0
        max_y = ylims(plt)[2]
    end
    plot!(plt,fill(frac_success,2), [0,max_y], label="Observed Rate")
    plt
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><div class="admonition is-question"><header class="admonition-header">Question:</header><div class="admonition-body"><p>Can we discuss how command line syntax works. What is happening when you type `julia –project -e "using Pkg; Pkg.instantiate();"?</p></div></div></div>


<div class="markdown"><ul><li><p>Often programs make use of packages of code that provide extra functionality beyond what's in the core language.</p></li><li><p>Packages inevitably change, so there are multiple versions. </p></li><li><p>In order to provide a reproducible environment, julia uses <code>Project.toml</code> which packages are needed and which versions are allowed.  </p></li><li><p>An optional <code>Manifest.toml</code> can specify precisely which versions of each package should be used.</p></li><li><p><code>julia --project=~/Astro416/lab3-eford</code> would tell julia to start using the environment specified in the directory <code>~/Astro416/lab3-eford</code>.  </p></li><li><p><code>julia --project</code> uses the environment provided in the current directory.</p></li><li><p><code>julia -e '1+1</code> tells to evaluate the quoted program and exit, rather than leaving you in the julia REPL.</p></li><li><p><code>using Pkg</code> tells Julia to import the package manager <code>Pkg</code> and allow us to direclty access functions exported by that package.</p></li><li><p><code>Pkg.instantiate()</code> tells julita to make sure all the packages specified in the current environment have been installed.</p></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><div class="admonition is-question"><header class="admonition-header">Question:</header><div class="admonition-body"><p>What is the difference between the <code>--</code> and <code>-</code>?</p></div></div></div>


<div class="markdown"><ul><li><p>A common convetion is to use <code>-</code> for one letter command-line options and <code>--</code> for command line options that use multiple characters.</p></li><li><p><code>-e</code> is short of <code>--eval</code>, so <code>julia --eval '1+1'</code> and <code>julia -e '1+1'</code>.</p></li><li><p>But <code>-p</code> is short for <code>--procs</code> (to use multiprocessing).</p></li><li><p><code>julia --help</code> or <code>julia -h</code> will show you more command line options.</p></li></ul></div>
